The paper proposes a new methodology for solving combinatorial optimization problems, specifically the permutation flowshop scheduling problem. The methodology is based on exploiting the property of neutrality in the fitness landscape, which is a common characteristic of many optimization problems. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) or Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-categories, as these fields often deal with optimization problems. Additionally, the paper proposes an iterated local search algorithm, which falls under the Operations Research (cs.OR) and Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science (cs.CE) sub-categories. Finally, the paper also analyzes the tradeoff between exploitation and exploration, which is a topic that falls under the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
